      "in general, if `E = ℗²`, and `f(n) = e_n`, then the convex hull of `{e_n, e_{n+1}, ...}` is not containing `0` as we said, but if we could find some point in all these convex hulls, we could take `g(n)` constant. \n\nBut perhaps the intersection of all these convex hulls is nonempty? \n\nThis is equivalent to saying that there exists `x ∈ E` such that for each `n`, `x ∈ convexHull {f(n), f(n+1), ...}`. \n\nIs this true? \n\nNo: take `E = ℝ`, `f(n) = n`. Then the convex hull of `{f(n), f(n+1), ...}` is `[n, ∞)`, and the intersection is empty. \n\nBut in this case, the norm is not bounded (`‖f(n)‖ = n`), but the problem requires `h_bdd`.\n\nHmm. \n\nAnother try: Take `E = ℝ²`, `f(n) = (1, 0)` if `n` is even and `(0, 1)` if `n` is odd. Then `‖f(n)‖ = 1` is bounded. \n\nNow, for `n = 0`, the convex hull of `{f(0), f(1), ...}` is `conv{(1, 0), (0, 1), (1, 0), ...} = conv{(1,0), (0,1)}`. \n\nFor `n = 1`, the convex hull is `conv{(0,1), (1,0), ...}` = same as before. \n\nIn that case, we could take `g(n) = ((1,0) + (0,1))/2 = (1/2,1/2)` for all `n`, and it lies in every convex hull. \n\nThis sequence `g(n)` is constant and thus tends to `(1/2, 1/2)`. \n\nSo in this case, we could take the constant sequence in the intersection of the convex hulls. \n\nBut is the intersection nonempty in general? \n\nNo, for `E = ℝ`, `f(n) = 1` if `n = 0`, else `f(n) = 2`. Then `h_bdd` is satisfied with `M = 2`. \n\nConvex hull of `Set.range fun m ↦ f (n + m)`:\n- For `n = 0`: `Set.range` is `{1, 2}`, convex hull is `[1,2]`.\n- For `n = 1`: `Set.range` is `{2}`, convex hull is `{2}`. \nBut then the intersection of `[1,2]` and `{2}` is `{2}`, so we can take `g(n) = 2`, which would work. \n\nAnother try: `f(0) = 1`, `f(1) = 0`, `f(2) = 2`, `f(n) = 2` for `n ≥ 2`. \n\nThen `h_bdd` holds. \n\n- The convex hull for `n = 0` is `conv{1, 0, 2, ...} = [0, 2]`.\n- For `n = 1`: `conv{0, 2, ...} = [0, ∞)`? No, because it is only `{f(1), f(2), ...} = {0, 2}`, convex hull `[0, 2]`.\nWait, actually: